{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585605"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:14:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:14:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14989"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14989"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.2,0.36,0.12,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7677"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115443"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7677"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14989"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97446"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4908"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5440"},{"type":"tags","id":"9979"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18762"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18765"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115443"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ET cell activation requires two distinct signals. The first signal occurs when the T cell receptor recognizes processed antigen presented by major histocompatibility complex molecules. The second essential signal involves co-stimulatory molecules that strengthen the interaction between T cells and antigen-presenting cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following co-stimulatory molecules on antigen-presenting cells binds to CD28 on T cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CD40","CD54","CD80/CD86","CD83","CD209"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe co-stimulatory molecule \u003Cstrong\u003ECD80/CD86\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as B7) on antigen-presenting cells binds to CD28 on T cells. This interaction provides the second signal necessary for full T cell activation. Without this co-stimulatory signal, T cells may become anergic rather than activated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECD40\u003C/strong\u003E binds to CD40L on T cells but is not the primary co-stimulatory molecule for CD28. \u003Cstrong\u003ECD54\u003C/strong\u003E (ICAM-1) is an adhesion molecule that binds to LFA-1. \u003Cstrong\u003ECD83\u003C/strong\u003E is a maturation marker on dendritic cells but does not provide co-stimulation. \u003Cstrong\u003ECD209\u003C/strong\u003E (DC-SIGN) is a pattern recognition receptor but not a co-stimulatory molecule.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["CD28 on T cells binds to B7 (CD80/CD86) on antigen-presenting cells to provide essential co-stimulation for T cell activation","T cell activation requires both antigen recognition via T cell receptor and co-stimulatory signals","Without proper co-stimulation, T cells become anergic rather than activated"],"references":["Esensten JH, Helou YA, Chopra G, Weiss A, Bluestone JA. CD28 Costimulation: From Mechanism to Therapy. Immunity. 2016 May 17;44(5):973-88. doi: 10.1016/j.immuni.2016.04.020. PMID: 27192564; PMCID: PMC4932896.","Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Janeway CA Jr, Travers P, Walport M, et al. Immunobiology: The Immune System in Health and Disease. 5th edition. New York: Garland Science; 2001. Chapter 9, The Humoral Immune Response. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK10752/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97446"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14989"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97446"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T18:25:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T18:26:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7677"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115443"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4908"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-14T17:03:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-14T17:03:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"ta